using System.Text;
using SkiaSharp;

var bounds = new SKRect(0, 0, 200, 200);

// Test 1: Read stream BEFORE canvas disposal (reporter's pattern)
Console.WriteLine("--- Test 1: Read stream BEFORE canvas disposal ---");
{
    using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
    using var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream);
    using var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream);
    using var paint = new SKPaint();
    paint.Color = SKColors.Red;
    canvas.DrawRect(new SKRect(10, 10, 100, 100), paint);
    var svgData = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(managedStream.ToArray());
    var hasClosingTag = svgData.Contains("</svg>");
    Console.WriteLine($"Has closing </svg> tag: {hasClosingTag}");
}

// Test 2: Read stream AFTER canvas disposal (correct pattern)
Console.WriteLine("--- Test 2: Read stream AFTER canvas disposal ---");
{
    var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
    using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, managedStream))
    {
        using var paint = new SKPaint();
        paint.Color = SKColors.Red;
        canvas.DrawRect(new SKRect(10, 10, 100, 100), paint);
    }
    var svgData = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(managedStream.ToArray());
    var hasClosingTag = svgData.Contains("</svg>");
    Console.WriteLine($"Has closing </svg> tag: {hasClosingTag}");
}

proposedResponse.body:
Thanks for the detailed report and SVG samples!

We were able to reproduce the missing `</svg>` tag. The SVG canvas writes the closing tag when the canvas is **disposed** (destroyed) — this is Skia's native behavior for finalizing the SVG document.

In your code, `using var` defers disposal to the end of the enclosing scope, so `managedStream.ToArray()` runs *before* the canvas is disposed and the closing tag is written.

**Workaround — use a scoped `using` block** so the canvas is disposed before you read the stream:

```csharp
var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, managedStream))
{
    // draw operations...
    canvas.DrawMeasurement(skiaRenderer, filename, file, CanvasSize, CanvasSize);
}
// Canvas is now disposed — closing </svg> tag has been written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

Note: you can pass the `MemoryStream` directly to `SKSvgCanvas.Create` — SkiaSharp will wrap it in an `SKManagedWStream` internally.

Your observation that `SKFileWStream` works is consistent with this — file output is typically read after everything is disposed, while `MemoryStream.ToArray()` is called inline before disposal.

**Tested versions:**
| Version | Result |
|---------|--------|
| 3.119.0 (reporter) | ❌ Missing tag (before disposal) / ✅ Present (after disposal) |
| 3.119.2 (latest) | ❌ Missing tag (before disposal) / ✅ Present (after disposal) |
| main (source) | ❌ Missing tag (before disposal) / ✅ Present (after disposal) |
